<DocsLayout title="Contributing" description="How to contribute to the sens.legal ecosystem.">
  <h1>Contributing</h1>

  <p>
    sens.legal is in alpha and we welcome contributors. Whether you are a
    developer, lawyer, or researcher, there are ways to get involved.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Pick a project: <a href="/projects/valter">Valter</a>, <a href="/projects/juca">Juca</a>, or <a href="/projects/leci">Leci</a></li>
    <li>Check the open issues on the project's GitHub repository</li>
    <li>Fork the repository and create a feature branch</li>
    <li>Submit a pull request with a clear description</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Repositories</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/sensdiego/Valter" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Valter</a> — Legal knowledge backend (Python, FastAPI)</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/sensdiego/juca" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Juca</a> — Frontend for lawyers (Next.js, TypeScript)</li>
    <li><a href="https://github.com/sensdiego/leci" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Leci</a> — Legislation backend (planning)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Areas Where We Need Help</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Legal domain expertise:</strong> reviewing accuracy of legal data models and terminology</li>
    <li><strong>Backend development:</strong> Python, FastAPI, Neo4j, PostgreSQL</li>
    <li><strong>Frontend development:</strong> Next.js, React, TypeScript</li>
    <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> improving docs, writing tutorials, translating content</li>
    <li><strong>Testing:</strong> expanding test coverage, edge cases, integration tests</li>
  </ul>

